06706nam a22008415i 9780773591141DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735911417 a10.1515/97807735911412doi  a(DE-B1597)656709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQA76.9.D5bW88 1997eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a004/.362211 aGhosh, Sukumar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSelf-Stabilizing Systems /cTed Herman, Sukumar Ghosh. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInternational Informatics Series ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCompositional Design of Multitolerant Repetitive Byzantine Agreement -- tDevelopment of Self-Stabilizing Distributed Algorithms using Transformation: Case Studies -- tThe Linear Alternator -- tSelf-Stabilizing ℓ-exclusion (Preliminary Version) -- tOn FTSS-Solvable Distributed Problems -- tCompositional Proofs of Self-stabilizing Protocols -- tDelay-Insensitive Stabilization -- tA Latency Optimal Superstabilizing Mutual Exclusion Protocol -- tMemory-Efficient Self-stabilizing Algorithm to Construct BFS Spanning Trees -- tSelf-stabilizing Universal Algorithms -- tTrade-offs in fault-containing self-stabilization -- tSelf-Stabilizing Multiple-Sender / Single-Receiver Protocol -- tPropagated Timestamps: A Scheme for the Stabilization of Maximum Flow Routing Protocols -- tDeductive Verification of Stabilizing Systems -- tSelf-Stabilizing Systems0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSelf- governing control is a defining characteristic of autonomous computing machinery. Autonomy implies some degree of independence, and when a system's ability to achieve its mission is independent of how it is initialized, the system is self-stabilizing. Application of self-stabilization to system and network components is motivated by core concerns of fault-tolerance in distributed systems. Self-stabilization is a solution to problems of transient memory faults and systems with dynamic reconfigurations. Research in self-stabilization explores many of the classic themes of distributed computing (distributed graph algorithms, mutual exclusion, distributed agreement). Recent papers combine self-stabilization with traditional forms of fault-tolerance, consider methodological issues for the design of self-stabilizing systems, investigate randomized techniques, and apply stabilization to new networking models. The workshop brings together concerns from theory and practice of self-stabilization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElectronic data processingxDistributed processingvCongresses. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbraham, Uri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAoral, Anish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArora, Anish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeauquier, Joffroy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerket, Karlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoldi, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, Jorge A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolev, Shlomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujiwara, Hideo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosh, Sukumar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGouda, Mohamed G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaddix, Furrnan, 